The period of Servius Tullius at Rome was then somewhat similar to that of Peisistratus—roughly contemporary—at Athens. The curia, in all its senses—military, territorial, political, religious—-was replaced by a wiser, because a wider, organisation. The needs and the responsibilities of a nation were beginning to be realised.

We have found it convenient to regard Numa as representa- tive of the older, native-bom religious beliefs (di Indzjgetes), and of the sterner Sabine ritual and rule3 and we may associate with the age of Servius Tullius the recognition of new cults (di Novensiles), introduced to the Romans and accepted by them in consequence of the increase of trade and other dealings with their Sabine, Latin, Greek, and Etruscan neighbourS. It is a period, then, of outside influence in religion ¹, justas the rise of the plebeians represents the influence of other elements in the state and constitution.
